04711nam a22006015i 9780226672144DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202019ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019014786  a9780226672144  a(DE-B1597)568279  a(OCoLC)1129690683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN1993.5.U6bP53 2020 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a791.430973223  aAP 452002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7520:1 aPippin, Robert B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFilmed Thought :bCinema as Reflective Form /cRobert B. Pippin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b66 color plates, 30 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSection I. Cinema as Reflective Form -- t1 Cinematic Reflection -- t2 Cinematic Self- Consciousness in Alfred Hitchcock’s Rear Window -- tSection II. Moral Variations -- t3 Devils & Angels in Pedro Almodóvar’s Talk to Her -- t4 Confounding Morality in Alfred Hitchcock’s Shadow of a Doubt -- tSection III. Social Pathologies -- t5 Cinematic Tone in Roman Polanski’s Chinatown: Can “Life” Itself Be “False”? -- t6 Love & Class in Douglas Sirk’s All That Heaven Allows -- tSection IV. Irony & Mutuality -- t7 Cinematic Irony: The Strange Case of Nicholas Ray’s Johnny Guitar -- t8 Passive & Active Skepticism in Nicholas Ray’s In a Lonely Place -- tSection V. Agency & Meaning -- t9 Vernacular Metaphysics: On Terrence Malick’s The Thin Red Line -- t10 Psychology Degree Zero? The Representation of Action in the Films of the Dardenne Brothers -- tAcknowledgments -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the rise of review sites and social media, films today, as soon as they are shown, immediately become the topic of debates on their merits not only as entertainment, but also as serious forms of artistic expression. Philosopher Robert B. Pippin, however, wants us to consider a more radical proposition: film as thought, as a reflective form. Pippin explores this idea through a series of perceptive analyses of cinematic masterpieces, revealing how films can illuminate, in a concrete manner, core features and problems of shared human life. Filmed Thought examines questions of morality in Almodóvar’s Talk to Her, goodness and naïveté in Hitchcock’s Shadow of a Doubt, love and fantasy in Sirk’s All That Heaven Allows, politics and society in Polanski’s Chinatown and Malick’s The Thin Red Line, and self-understanding and understanding others in Nicholas Ray’s In a Lonely Place and in the Dardennes brothers' oeuvre. In each reading, Pippin pays close attention to what makes these films exceptional as technical works of art (paying special attention to the role of cinematic irony) and as intellectual and philosophical achievements. Throughout, he shows how films offer a view of basic problems of human agency from the inside and allow viewers to think with and through them. Captivating and insightful, Filmed Thought shows us what it means to take cinema seriously not just as art, but as thought, and how this medium provides a singular form of reflection on what it is to be human.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMotion picturesxAesthetics. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aAesthetic.  aCavell.  aSelf-knowledge.  aSkepticism.  acinematic.  aform.  airony.  areflection.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226672144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226672144/original  a978-3-11-071194-